<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08077c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08077c">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08077c"> 77(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> So all my best is dressing / old words new / Spending again what is / already spent</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A modern Englishman, realizing the great advantage his language possesses in its power of making words serve in new functions, might make Shakespeare&apos;s lines his own in a different sense: &lsquo;So all my best is dressing old words new, / Spending againe what is already spent&rsquo;. <font color="green">[Sonnet 76]</font> <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 169</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
